#* {{quote-book|en|author=Walter W[illiam] Rouse Ball|authorlink=W. W. Rouse Ball|chapter=Egyptian and Phœnecian Mathematics|title=A Short Account of the History of Mathematics|location=London; New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan and Co.]]|year=1888|page=6|pageurl=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015038945906&view=1up&seq=38|oclc=1125887121|passage=Before leaving the question of early arithmetic I should mention that for practical purposes the almost universal use of the '''abacus''' or swan-pan rendered it easy to add or subtract, or even to multiply and divide, without any knowledge of theoretical mathematics. [...] [I]t will be sufficient here to say that they afford a concrete way of representing a number in the decimal scale, and enable the results of addition and subtraction to be obtained by a merely mechanical process.}}
